Rule Agent — Evaluation Matrix
Tier 0 — Shared business/fraud metrics (not an evaluation layer — the data itself, flowing through the pipeline)
App count · OTP failure rate · device velocity · IP velocity · approval rate · decline reason distribution · fraud score distribution

Tier 1 — Per-tool operational health (inline, every 3-hr cycle, captured via AgentCore Observability)

Tool	Evaluates	Metrics
Kafka Live Stats	Did it build the current matrix correctly?	Processing latency · missing records % · aggregation accuracy · schema validation success · matrix generation success
Redshift Stats	Did it return the right baseline?	Baseline freshness (vs. calculated_at) · query latency · baseline coverage · retrieval success
Compare/Anomaly	Did rules execute correctly, mechanically?	Rules executed count · rules triggered count · rule execution latency · execution error rate · correct segment matched (join accuracy — lives here, not Redshift Stats, since Redshift Stats bulk-fetches everything)
Tier 2 — Orchestrator evaluation (inline, per cycle)

Component	Evaluates	Metrics
AgentCore Runtime	Correct orchestration	Were all 3 tools called? Did the 2 parallel ones actually run concurrently? Were retries needed? Overall workflow completion time? Tool call success rate?
Tier 3 — Fraud-detection accuracy (offline, batch — NOT per-request; the layer ChatGPT's list was missing)

Evaluates	Metrics	How
Was the anomaly call actually correct?	Precision · recall · F1 · false-positive rate · false-negative rate — per rule	Replay historical labeled cases (Amazon PL attack, One Pay attack, Floor & Décor attack) through Compare's skills, offline; compare flagged output vs. known ground truth